Discrete STFT: Frequency Resolution


In this notebook, we discuss how to increase the frequency resolution by suitably padding the windowed sections in the STFT computation. For details on the STFT, we refer to Section 2.1.4 of [Mller, FMP, Springer 2015]. Reference to technique.

DFT with Increased Frequency Resolution¶

Let $x\in \mathbb{R}^N$ be discrete signal of length $N\in\mathbb{N}$ with samples $x(0), x(1), \ldots, x(N-1)$. Given the sampling $F_\mathrm{s}$, we assume that $x$ is obtained by sampling a continues-time signal $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$. Then, the discrete Fourier transform (DFT) $X := \mathrm{DFT}_N \cdot x$ can be interpreted as an approximation of $\hat{f}$ for certain frequencies (see Equation (2.132) of [Mller, FMP, Springer 2015]):

$$ X(k) := \sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x(n) \exp(-2 \pi i k n / N) \approx {F_\mathrm{s}} \cdot \hat{f} \left(k \cdot \frac{F_\mathrm{s}}{N}\right) $$

for $k\in[0:N-1]$. Thus, the index $k$ of $X(k)$ corresponds to the physical frequency

\begin{equation} F_\mathrm{coef}^N(k) := \frac{k\cdot F_\mathrm{s}}{N} \end{equation}

given in Hertz. Intuitively speaking, the discrete Fourier transform introduces a linear frequency resolution of $F_\mathrm{s}/N$ that depends on the size $N$ of the $\mathrm{DFT}_N$. To increase the frequency resolution, one idea is to increase the size of the DFT. Let $L\in\mathbb{N}$ with $L\geq N$. Then, we apply zero padding to the right of the signal $x$ obtaining the signal $\tilde{x}\in \mathbb{R}^L$:

\begin{equation} \tilde{x}(n) :=\left\{\begin{array}{ll} x(n) ,& \,\,\mbox{for}\,\, n \in[0:N-1],\\ 0, & \,\,\mbox{for}\,\, n \in[N:L-1]. \end{array}\right. \end{equation}

Applying a $\mathrm{DFT}_L$, we obtain:

$$ \tilde{X}(k) = \mathrm{DFT}_L \cdot \tilde{x} = \sum_{n=0}^{L-1} \tilde{x}(n) \exp(-2 \pi i k n / L) = \sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x(n) \exp(-2 \pi i k n / L) \approx {F_\mathrm{s}} \cdot \hat{f} \left(k \cdot \frac{F_\mathrm{s}}{L}\right) $$

for $k\in[0:L-1]$. The coefficient $\tilde{X}(k)$ now corresponds to the physical frequency

\begin{equation} F_\mathrm{coef}^L(k) := \frac{k\cdot F_\mathrm{s}}{L}, \end{equation}

thus introducing a linear frequency resolution of $F_\mathrm{s}/L$. For example, if $L=2N$, the frequency resolution is increased by a factor of $2$. In other words, the longer DFT results in more frequency bins that are more closely spaced. However, note that this trick does not improve the approximation quality of the DFT (the number of summands in the Riemann approximation is still $N$). Only, the linear sampling of the frequency axis is refined when using $L\geq N$ and zero padding. The following example compares $\mathrm{DFT}_N \cdot x$ with $\mathrm{DFT}_L \cdot \tilde{x}$.

import numpy as np
import scipy
from  matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import matplotlib
%matplotlib inline
import librosa

Fs = 64
duration = 2
omega1 = 7
omega2 = 17
N = duration * Fs
t = np.arange(0, N) * 1 / Fs
t1 = t[:N//2]
t2 = t[N//2:]

x1 = 1.0 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * omega1 * t1)
x2 = 0.7 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * omega2 * t2)
x = np.concatenate((x1, x2))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 2))
ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(x, c='k')
plt.title('Orginal signal of size $N$=%d' %N)
plt.xlabel('Time (samples)')
plt.xlim([0, N-1])
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
Y = np.abs(np.fft.fft(x)) / Fs
plt.plot(Y, c='k')
plt.title('MagnitudeDFT of original signal using $N$=%d' %N)
plt.xlabel('Frequency (bins)')
plt.xlim([0, N-1])
plt.tight_layout()

L = 2*N
pad_len = L-N
t_tilde = np.concatenate((t, np.arange(len(x), len(x) + pad_len) / Fs))
x_tilde = np.concatenate((x, np.zeros(pad_len)))
                         
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 2))
ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(x_tilde, c='k')
plt.title('Padded signal of size $L$=%d' %L)
plt.xlabel('Time (samples)')
plt.xlim([0, L-1])
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
Y_tilde = np.abs(np.fft.fft(x_tilde)) / Fs
plt.plot(Y_tilde, c='k')
plt.title('Magnitude DFT of padded signal using $L$=%d' %L)
plt.xlabel('Frequency (bins)')
plt.xlim([0, L-1])
plt.tight_layout()

The next code example implements a function for computing the DFT with increased frequency resolution, where all parameters are interpreted in a physical way (in terms of seconds and Hertz).

In [2]:
def compute_plot_DFT_extended(t, x, Fs, L):
    N = len(x)
    pad_len = L-N
    t_tilde = np.concatenate((t, np.arange(len(x), len(x) + pad_len) / Fs))
    x_tilde = np.concatenate((x, np.zeros(pad_len)))
    Y = np.abs(np.fft.fft(x_tilde)) / Fs    
    Y = Y[:L//2]
    freq = np.arange(L//2)*Fs/L
    # freq = np.fft.fftfreq(L, d=1/Fs)
    # freq = freq[:L//2]
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 2))
    
    ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    plt.plot(t_tilde, x_tilde, c='k')
    plt.title('Signal of size $N$=%d' %N)
    plt.xlabel('Time (seconds)')
    plt.xlim([t[0], t[-1]])
    
    ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    plt.plot(t_tilde, x_tilde, c='k')
    plt.title('Padded signal of size $L$=%d' %L)
    plt.xlabel('Time (seconds)')
    plt.xlim([t_tilde[0], t_tilde[-1]])    
    
    ax2 = plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    plt.plot(freq, Y, c='k')
    plt.title('Magnitude DFT of padded signal using $L$=%d' %L)
    plt.xlabel('Frequency (Hz)')
    plt.xlim([freq[0], freq[-1]])
    plt.tight_layout()           
    
    ax1 = 1
    ax2 = 2
    return ax1, ax2    

    
N = len(x)
L = N
ax1, ax2 = compute_plot_DFT_extended(t, x, Fs, L)

L = 2*N
ax1, ax2 = compute_plot_DFT_extended(t, x, Fs, L)

L = 4*N
ax1, ax2 = compute_plot_DFT_extended(t, x, Fs, L)

STFT with Increased Frequency Resolution¶

We now show how the same zero-padding strategy can be used to increase the frequency resolution of an STFT. The librosa function librosa.stft implements this idea by means of the two parameters n_fft (correponding to $L$) and win_length (correponding to $N$). Care has to be taken when converting the parameters to the physical domain. Our example is the note C4 played by a violin (with vibrato).

We now compute an STFT with zero-padding. In the visualization, the axis are shown in terms of time frames and frequency bins.

In [4]:
def compute_stft(x, Fs, N, H, L=N, pad_mode='constant', center=True, print_para=False):    
    X = librosa.stft(x, n_fft=L, hop_length=H, win_length=N, 
                 window='hann', pad_mode=pad_mode, center=center)
    Y = np.log(1 + 100 * np.abs(X) ** 2)
    F_coef = librosa.fft_frequencies(sr=Fs, n_fft=L)
    T_coef = librosa.frames_to_time(np.arange(X.shape[1]), sr=Fs, hop_length=H)
    if print_para:
        print('Y.shape = [%4d, %4d], Fs = %d, N = %4d, L = %4d, freq = [%4.1f, %4.1f], freq_res = %4.1f, t = [%4.3f, %4.3f]' 
              %(Y.shape[0],Y.shape[1], Fs, N, L, F_coef[0], F_coef[-1], F_coef[1]-F_coef[0], T_coef[0], T_coef[-1]))    
    return Y, F_coef, T_coef

N = 256
H = 64
color = 'gray_r' 
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))

plt.subplot(1,3,1)
L = N
Y, F_coef, T_coef = compute_stft(x, Fs, N, H, L, print_para=True)
plt.imshow(Y, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower'); 
plt.xlabel('Time (frames)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (bins)')
plt.colorbar()

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
L = 2*N
Y, F_coef, T_coef = compute_stft(x, Fs, N, H, L, print_para=True)
plt.imshow(Y, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower'); 
plt.xlabel('Time (frames)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (bins)')
plt.colorbar()

plt.subplot(1,3,3)
L = 4*N
Y, F_coef, T_coef = compute_stft(x, Fs, N, H, L, print_para=True)
plt.imshow(Y, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower'); 
plt.xlabel('Time (frames)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (bins)')
plt.colorbar()
plt.tight_layout()

Reshaping the Frequency Axis Using Interpolation Techniques¶

As an alternative of using a larger DFT based on zero-padding to increase the STFT frequency resolution, one may simply use interpolation techniques along the frequency direction to adjust the frequency resolution. The following code example shows how to use the function scipy.inperploate.interp1d to implement this idea.

In [6]:
from scipy.interpolate import interp1d

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 3))

X = librosa.stft(x, n_fft=N, hop_length=H, win_length=N, window='hann', pad_mode='constant', center=True)
Y = np.log(1 + 100 * np.abs(X) ** 2)
T_coef = np.arange(0, X.shape[1]) * H/Fs
F_coef = np.arange(0, N//2+1) * Fs/N

L = N
plt.subplot(1,3,1)
extent=[T_coef[0], T_coef[-1], F_coef[0], F_coef[-1]]
plt.imshow(Y, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower', extent=extent); 
plt.xlabel('Time (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.title('L=%d' %L)
plt.ylim(plt_interval_freq_hz)
plt.xlim(plt_interval_seconds)
plt.colorbar()

L = 2*N
F_coef_new = np.arange(0, L//2+1) * Fs/L
compute_Y_interp = interp1d(F_coef, Y, kind='linear', axis=0)
Y_interp = compute_Y_interp(F_coef_new)
plt.subplot(1,3,2)
extent=[T_coef[0], T_coef[-1], F_coef_new[0], F_coef_new[-1]]
plt.imshow(Y_interp, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower', extent=extent); 
plt.xlabel('Time (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.title('L=%d' %L)
plt.ylim(plt_interval_freq_hz)
plt.xlim(plt_interval_seconds)
plt.colorbar()

L = 4*N
F_coef_new = np.arange(0, L//2+1) * Fs/L
compute_Y_interp = interp1d(F_coef, Y, kind='linear', axis=0)
Y_interp = compute_Y_interp(F_coef_new)
plt.subplot(1,3,3)
extent=[T_coef[0], T_coef[-1], F_coef_new[0], F_coef_new[-1]]
plt.imshow(Y_interp, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower', extent=extent); 
plt.xlabel('Time (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.title('L=%d' %L)
plt.ylim(plt_interval_freq_hz)
plt.xlim(plt_interval_seconds)
plt.colorbar()
plt.tight_layout()

This interpolation techniques can be also used for a non-linear deformation of the frequency axis. In the following code example, the linearly spaced frequency axis is transformed into a logarithmically spaced axis.

In [7]:
def log_spec_via_interp(Y, F_coef, R, F_min, F_max):
    # R = resolution (cents)
    # F_min = minimum frequency
    # F_max = maximum frequency
    n_bins = np.ceil(1200 * np.log2(F_max / F_min) / R).astype(int)
    F_coef_log = 2 ** (np.arange(0, n_bins) * R / 1200) * F_min
    compute_Y_interp = interp1d(F_coef, Y, kind='linear', axis=0)
    Y_interp = compute_Y_interp(F_coef_log)
    F_coef_cents = np.arange(0, n_bins) * 1200 * np.log2(F_max / F_min)/n_bins
    return Y_interp, F_coef_log, F_coef_cents

F_min = 100
F_max = 3200

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.subplot(1,3,1)
extent=[T_coef[0], T_coef[-1], F_coef[0], F_coef[-1]]
plt.imshow(Y, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower', extent=extent); 
plt.xlabel('Time (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.title('Linear frequency axis')
plt.ylim([F_min, F_max])
plt.colorbar()

R = 50
Y_interp, F_coef_log, F_coef_cents = log_spec_via_interp(Y, F_coef, R, F_min, F_max)

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
extent=[T_coef[0], T_coef[-1], F_coef_cents[0], F_coef_cents[-1]]
plt.imshow(Y_interp, cmap=color , aspect='auto', origin='lower', extent=extent); 
plt.xlabel('Time (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (cents)')
plt.title('Log-frequency axis')
plt.title('Log-frequency axis with R=%d'%R)
plt.colorbar()

R = 10

extent=[T_coef[0], T_coef[-1], F_coef_cents[0], F_coef_cents[-1]]
